pullRequest.body:
This change proves that `Grothendieck.pre F G` is an equivalence if `G` is an equivalence. An essential ingredient in the proof is the `transport` construction: Given a morphism in the base category, `transport` yields a map between fibers of the Grothendieck construction.

This PR is part of the effort to prove the Freyd-Mitchell embedding theorem.

nodes.body: We should not use `Equivalance.mk` as it leaves out a compatibility which we should be able to obtain here.

```suggestion
@[simps]
def transport (x : Grothendieck F) {c : C} (t : x.base ⟶ c) : Grothendieck F :=
```
I'm unsure whether this would be an improvement. `transport` is not a super-simple definition. If simp unfolds it automatically, expressions might get more complicated quickly.

```suggestion
@[simps]
def toTransport (x : Grothendieck F) {c : C} (t : x.base ⟶ c) : x ⟶ x.transport t :=
  ⟨t, 𝟙 _⟩
```

```suggestion
  hom := ⟨α.inv, eqToHom (by
    dsimp
    rw [← Functor.comp_obj, ← Cat.comp_eq_comp, ← F.map_comp, α.hom_inv_id, F.map_id,
      Cat.id_obj])⟩
  inv := x.toTransport α.hom
  hom_inv_id := Grothendieck.ext _ _ (by simp) (by simp)
  inv_hom_id := Grothendieck.ext _ _ (by simp) (by simp)
```

```suggestion
    pre F G ≅ map (whiskerRight α.hom F) ⋙ (pre F H) :=
```

```suggestion
def preInv (G : D ≌ C) : Grothendieck F ⥤ Grothendieck (G.functor ⋙ F) :=
  map (F.leftUnitor.inv ≫ whiskerRight G.counitInv F ≫ (Functor.associator _ _ _).hom) ⋙
    Grothendieck.pre (G.functor ⋙ F) G.inverse
```
I removed `leftUnitor` and `associator` -- they are just `rfl` and somehow seem to break `preEquivalence`.

```suggestion
def mapWhiskerLeftIsoConjPreMap {F' : C ⥤ Cat} (G : D ≌ C) (α : F ⟶ F') :
    map (whiskerLeft G.functor α) ≅
      (preEquivalence F G).functor ⋙ map α ⋙ (preEquivalence F' G).inverse := by
  apply Iso.symm
  apply preEquivalence F' G |>.congrRight.fullyFaithfulFunctor.preimageIso
  exact isoWhiskerLeft ((preEquivalence F G).functor ⋙ map α) (preEquivalence F' G).counitIso
```
(The docstring should also be updated.)

```suggestion
def preEquivalence (G : D ≌ C) : Grothendieck (G.functor ⋙ F) ≌ Grothendieck F where
  functor := pre F G.functor
  inverse := preInv F G
```
Also, the unit and counit isos should not be constructed using tactics. This would create issues when we want to unfold these definitions.

Now the construction of `unitIso` begins with a `refine` tactic and its only hole is propositional (`eqToIso ?_`). I find it more readable this way, compared to directly filling the hole.

As far as I know, using `refine` should be okay as it just helps me build an expression in multiple steps. Is it fine this way or should I really use term mode here?
Yes, `refine` is very much ok, especially when the holes are props. I will have a closer look at the PR in the next few days.

I would think that the following definition could be useful:
```lean
@[simps]
def isoMk {X Y : Grothendieck F} (e₁ : X.base ≅ Y.base)
    (e₂ : (F.map e₁.hom).obj X.fiber ≅ Y.fiber) :
    X ≅ Y where
  hom := ⟨e₁.hom, e₂.hom⟩
  inv := ⟨e₁.inv, (F.map e₁.inv).map e₂.inv ≫
    eqToHom (Functor.congr_obj (F.mapIso e₁).hom_inv_id X.fiber)⟩
  hom_inv_id := Grothendieck.ext _ _ (by simp) (by simp)
  inv_hom_id := Grothendieck.ext _ _ (by simp) (by
    have := Functor.congr_hom (F.mapIso e₁).inv_hom_id e₂.inv
    dsimp at this
    simp [this])
```
Indeed, `transportIso` becomes:
```lean
@[simps!]
def transportIso (x : Grothendieck F) {c : C} (α : x.base ≅ c) :
    x.transport α.hom ≅ x :=
  (isoMk α (Iso.refl _)).symm
```

```suggestion
      (preEquivalence F G).functor ⋙ map α ⋙ (preEquivalence F' G).inverse :=
  (Functor.rightUnitor _).symm ≪≫ isoWhiskerLeft _ (preEquivalence F' G).unitIso
```
